1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,000
Welcome to today's episode where we discuss the latest developments in artificial intelligence.

2
00:00:05,000 --> 00:00:10,000
Large language models have been making significant progress in reasoning capabilities.

3
00:00:10,000 --> 00:00:15,000
Companies like OpenAI and Google are competing to build the most capable models.

4
00:00:15,000 --> 00:00:20,000
The compute requirements for training these models continue to grow exponentially.

5
00:00:20,000 --> 00:00:25,000
New chip architectures from Nvidia and AMD are designed specifically for AI workloads.

6
00:00:25,000 --> 00:00:30,000
The H100 GPU has become the standard hardware for training large models.

7
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:35,000
Meanwhile regulation of AI systems is becoming a major policy topic.

8
00:00:35,000 --> 00:00:40,000
The European Union has passed the AI Act which creates new compliance requirements.

9
00:00:40,000 --> 00:00:45,000
Companies must now classify their AI systems by risk level under the new framework.

10
00:00:45,000 --> 00:00:50,000
In the United States Congress is still debating various approaches to AI governance.

11
00:00:50,000 --> 00:00:55,000
Some lawmakers favor a light touch approach while others want strict regulations.

12
00:00:55,000 --> 00:01:00,000
The debate around AI safety continues to intensify as models become more capable.

13
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:05,000
Researchers are working on alignment techniques to ensure AI systems behave as intended.

14
00:01:05,000 --> 00:01:10,000
Constitutional AI and reinforcement learning from human feedback are two key approaches.

15
00:01:10,000 --> 00:01:15,000
The open source community has also made impressive progress with models like Llama and Mistral.

16
00:01:15,000 --> 00:01:20,000
These open models are enabling smaller companies and researchers to experiment with AI.

17
00:01:20,000 --> 00:01:25,000
That wraps up our discussion for today. Thanks for watching and see you next time.
